{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18252"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18252"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.31,0.04,0.08,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77956"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10966"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26754"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77956"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELooking for the Trendelenburg sign is a standard part of the physical examination of an individual\u0027s hip and relevant musculature when assessing functionality.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following movements occurs at the hip joint when the Trendelenburg sign is present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abduction","Adduction","Extension","Flexion","Subversion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Trendelenburg sign is a clinical test used to assess the strength of the hip abductor muscles, particularly the gluteus medius and minimus. It is observed when a person stands on one leg, and the pelvis drops on the side opposite to the stance leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen the Trendelenburg sign is present, the hip on the stance leg undergoes \u003Cstrong\u003Eadduction\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because the hip abductor muscles, particularly the gluteus medius and minimus, are weak or non-functional, leading to a drop of the pelvis on the opposite side.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbduction\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the movement that the hip abductors normally perform to keep the pelvis level\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtension\u003C/strong\u003E - This movement involves straightening the hip joint, not related to the Trendelenburg sign\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexion\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves bending the hip joint, not related to the Trendelenburg sign\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubversion\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a recognised movement at the hip joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Trendelenburg sign is often seen in conditions affecting the hip joint or the superior gluteal nerve, which innervates the hip abductor muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Trendelenburg sign indicates weakness in the hip abductor muscles, particularly the gluteus medius and minimus.","When the Trendelenburg sign is present, the pelvis drops on the side opposite to the stance leg, indicating adduction of the hip on the stance leg.","The Trendelenburg sign is commonly associated with conditions affecting the hip joint or the superior gluteal nerve."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/","Gogu S, Gandbhir VN. Trendelenburg Sign. 2022 Nov 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310447"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18252"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T21:01:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T21:01:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10966"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77956"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71"